        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-12T16:26:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "closeFile / readFile / writeFile / seekFile should be methods of an abstract FileHandle class instead. The FileSystem class itself should only be used to create FileHandle instances (opening / creating files), and performing tests (like System::pathIsDir() but taking const references to FilePath instances instead).",
      "revId": "09fe79086cc6ee355b14c1ec88d94232a11916a9",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9dc4c07e_ae8f8b17",
        "filename": "android/base/files/FileSystem.h",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 67,
      "author": {
        "id": 1087048
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-12T17:20:23Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The reason I wanted to put all this in one interface is because it makes it easier when unit testing. With a separate FileHandle class the TestFileSystem would have to return another implementation of FileHandle. That also means that FileHandle would have to be an interface or at least that everything would have to be virtual. So it seems to require a lot more classes to support testing.\n\nInstead I was thinking of having this as the low level interface and then creating a class File that exposes a better interface and RAII mechanics for lifetime management. The FileSystem interface would then never really be used by clients, it\u0027s more of an implementation detail that allows for easier unit testing.",
      "parentUuid": "fde93cd0_a2ffba7c",
      "revId": "09fe79086cc6ee355b14c1ec88d94232a11916a9",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
